@article{Fenner2016,
   abstract = {The status of fisheries around the world is controversial, with some of the most prominent fisheries scientists often divided into two camps, one that is more supportive of fishing (e.g., Hilborn, 2006) and one that is more supportive of conservation (e.g., Pauly, 2009). There are various definitions of Marine Protected Areas (MPAs), from strict no-take areas to " marine managed areas " which are not necessarily completely closed all the time. Here, I examine some of the arguments about MPAs, with particular attention to coral reef fisheries, and by MPA I refer mainly to no-take areas. There are now 7 billion people and the number is increasing, and fisheries are a critical protein source for many. The global fish catch is now so large it is limited by global ocean primary productivity (Chassot et al., 2010). Meantime, fisheries management has had some spectacular failures. Canada had world class fishery experts who proclaimed the cod fishery to be healthy and yet it collapsed, losing a $2 billion a year fishery (Kurlanski, 2010), which is only now recovering decades later. Some fisheries scientists show signs of irritation at the repetition of such stories, calling them the " litany " . Some complain that people still refer to papers that reported that the world's big predatory fish (like tuna and cod) are 80% depleted, maintaining that such figures were not based on strong science (it was not a stock assess-ment). They have written that there are at least 3 other major myths about fisheries commonly cited by the press and provide documenta-tion that the myths are wrong (Hilborn, 2016). Several of those with more fisheries-supportive views joined with those who have more conservationist views to review the large fisheries of the world in a paper which found that there were fisheries that are overfished, others that are fully fished, those that are in recovery; some in all categories (Worm, et al., 2009). Recently, another paper has reported that a survey of 75% of the world's fisheries revealed that the " Current status is highly heterogeneous—the median fishery is in poor health (overfished, with further overfishing occurring), although 32% of fisheries are in good biological, although not necessarily economic, condition " (Costello et al., 2016). This paper was another collaboration between those with the two viewpoints and which has been accepted or praised by both sides (Howard, 2016), giving it strong credibility. Other recent papers have pointed out that there are few fisheries left that are not fully fished, and a recent paper (Pauly and Zeller, 2016) presents data showing that the total world fish catch has been declining. MPA advocates say that protecting a certain proportion of the area protects a proportion of the total fish stock, insuring that a species doesn't become badly overfished. Fisheries scientists have criticized MPAs saying that they decrease total fish catch by closing off areas to fishing, cause hardship to fishermen who likely have to go farther and to more dangerous areas to fish, and which cause fishing effort to be concentrated into a smaller area, thus depleting those fish faster. These arguments appear to be based not on empirical data, but more on a series of assumptions such as that closing fishing areas causes total fish catch to decrease, fishermen to have to go farther, and that fishing effort stays constant and depletes fish in the open areas faster. On coral reefs, fishermen sometimes move their effort to just outside the MPA boundaries, presumably because they hope to catch more of the " spillover " fish there. Concentrating fishing efforts near MPA bound-aries may mean that the areas open to fishing might not become more overfished. Healthier populations in an MPA with larger females producing more eggs could support populations outside the MPA because the number of eggs is exponentially larger in larger fish, and total recruitment can be increased with just a few more very large individuals in an MPA (outside the MPA fishing removes most large individuals). Fisheries scientists point out that MPAs work best on fish species that are sedentary, because those fish don't swim far enough for more than a small proportion to swim outside the MPA. However, that means that their criticisms of MPAs are not so relevant to coral reefs, where most fish species are relatively sedentary (Green et al., 2015). MPAs may work well with coral reef fish even if they don't work well},
