   abstract = {A model of disease dynamics in an exploited stock was developed to assess the impact of the recent outbreak of Ichthyophonus hoferi in North Sea herring. Rates of infection by the disease and mortality rates of infected fish were estimated from field observations of prevalence, relative abundance, and commercial catches. At the height of the outbreak infection rates and mortality rates were about 0.4 year1 and 1.5 year1, respectively. Parameterization of infection rate as a year-class and age effect was more complex and did not provide a better fit than a year and age parameterization. The impact of I. hoferi on the North Sea herring stock was estimated to be significant but not catastrophic. Had the outbreak not occurred (but with catches being the same), the stock size would have been some 21% higher in 1994. Had the outbreak not occurred (but with fishing mortality being the same), the stock would have been 11% higher in 1994 and the catches from 1991 to 1994 would have been 9.6% higher. The consequences of using a standard stock assessment model in which nonfishing mortality is assumed constant when this assumption is violated are also assessed. A simple model is used to indicate the importance of disease-induced mortality.},
